Plot Caller Comparisons

C. Savonen for ALSF CCDL

2019

Purpose: After running the initial analyses of each variant caller and merging the data with 03-merge_callers.R, this notebook plots these data in a series of plots to compare the performance of the callers.

Summary of Findings:

Due to some of the findings here, I suggest we should move forward with mutations called by Strelka2, Mutect2, and Lancet. And, due to it’s oversensitivity that VarDict’s data can be dropped entirely.

Individual Caller’s Reports

  • Lancet
  • MuTect2
  • Strelka2
  • Vardict

Notable Findings:

  • VarDict calls more mutations than any of the other callers. Many of these have very low suggesting that some may be sequencing errors.

  • Mutect2, Strelka2, and Lancet do have plenty of mutations in common.

Outline of analyses completed:

  • Upset graph
  • VAF of combinations of callers
  • Base changes by caller
  • VAF distributions by caller
  • TMB distributions by caller
  • VAF correlations between callers
  • TMB correlations between callers

Usage

To run this from the command line, use:

Rscript -e "rmarkdown::render('analyses/snv-callers/compare_snv_callers_plots.Rmd', 
                              clean = TRUE)"

This assumes you are in the top directory of the repository.

rr vaf_long <- vaf_df %>% dplyr::group_by(mutation_id, caller) %>% dplyr::summarize(vaf = mean(vaf)) %>% dplyr::distinct(mutation_id, caller, vaf, .keep_all = TRUE) %>% tidyr::spread(caller, vaf) %>% tibble::column_to_rownames(_id)
